        <span class="eyebrow">Teaching · Research Methods &amp; Statistics</span>
        <h1>Courses</h1>
        <p class="thesis">
          Anyone can now compute a statistic in seconds; almost no one can say whether it should be believed.
          That gap — between an answer and a <em>defensible</em> one — is what my teaching is about. In an age
          of automated analysis, methodological judgment is the one skill a machine cannot supply, and it is
          the skill these courses are built to develop.
        </p>
        <p class="pull">I don't teach students to run the test. I teach them to know what the test can, and cannot, say.</p>
      </section>

      <!-- COURSE I -->
      <section class="section rv">
        <div class="section-eyebrow">Featured course</div>
        <article class="course">
          <div class="course-head">
            <span class="code-badge">RM 0301</span>
            <h2>Research Methods &amp; Statistics</h2>
            <div class="course-meta">
              <span>Undergraduate</span><span class="dot">·</span>
              <span>Harris-Stowe State University</span><span class="dot">·</span>
              <span>Online</span>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="course-body">
            <p class="lead">
              A first, serious encounter with how social knowledge is actually made — from a vague curiosity to
              a question that can be answered, from raw numbers to a claim you could defend in front of a skeptic.
              Statistics here is not a set of buttons to press but a way of reasoning under uncertainty.
            </p>

            <div class="subh">The arc of the course</div>
            <div class="arc">
              <span class="step">Question</span><span class="sep">→</span>
              <span class="step">Design</span><span class="sep">→</span>
              <span class="step">Evidence</span><span class="sep">→</span>
              <span class="step">Analysis</span><span class="sep">→</span>
              <span class="step end">A defensible claim</span>
            </div>

            <div class="subh">What students learn to do</div>
            <ul class="outcomes">
              <li>Turn a curiosity into a researchable question and a testable hypothesis.</li>
              <li>Choose and justify a research design — and know its blind spots.</li>
              <li>Reason about sampling, measurement, and validity before touching data.</li>
              <li>Run and read core statistics: description, association, inference.</li>
              <li>Interpret results honestly — including what the numbers cannot show.</li>
              <li>Use AI and software as tools, while owning the judgment themselves.</li>
            </ul>

            <div class="subh">How it is designed — for the AI age</div>
            <div class="design-note">
              <p>
                The course is built around a single, <b>scaffolded original research project</b> that grows
                week by week — proposal, design, analysis, and a final presentation — rather than one-off,
                easily-outsourced problem sets. Assessment rewards <b>reasoning shown, not answers produced</b>,
                which makes the work resistant to being generated wholesale and keeps the learning where it
                belongs: in the student's own judgment. A transparent 1,000-point structure makes every
                expectation legible from day one.
              </p>
            </div>

